Vessel Segmentation Dataset¶

The purpose of this notebook is to:¶

  1. Display the dataset which will be utilized in the AHA project
  2. Display the input to stage 2 of our model
  3. Demonstrate some of the key augmentation methods to prevent overfitting

About dataset¶

  • 119 images
  • 512 x 512 grayscale images (original input)
  • Stage 2 input: 512 x 512 x 3 channels (original input, stage 1 segmentation map, edge map of stage 1 segmentation map)

Test some of the transformations¶

Note: augment_imageset performs the following transformations (each can be individually set):¶

  • Horizontal and Vertical flips (one or the other)
  • Rotations
  • Translations
  • Top and bottom hat transforms (one or the other)
  • Random Gaussian and Salt & Pepper Noise (one or the other) #### Uses skimage, skimage.morphology, and cv2
In [6]:
img_x = stage_1_train_x_imgs[-1]
img_y = stage_1_train_y_imgs[-1]

Augment images¶

In [8]:
# quick function to display augmented images with 20% chance of of being augmented for a given augmentation
def display_augmentations(img_x, img_y):
    new_x, new_y = augment_imageset(img_x, img_y, probability_threshold=0.2, flip=True, rotate=True, 
                                translate=True, tophat=True, noise=True)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
    fig.add_subplot(121)
    plt.imshow(np.squeeze(new_x), cmap='gray')
    fig.add_subplot(122)
    plt.imshow(np.squeeze(new_y), cmap='gray')
In [9]:
display_augmentations(img_x, img_y)

Above, you can see a white top-hat transformation, rotation and flip. Let's "roll the dice again":¶

  • The top-hat filter, or white top-hat is used to enhance bright objects in a darker background.
In [10]:

Augment images¶

In [15]:
# quick function to display augmented images with 20% chance of of being augmented for a given augmentation
def stage_2_augmentations(img_x, img_y):
    new_x, new_y = augment_imageset(img_x, img_y, probability_threshold=0.2, flip=True, rotate=True, 
                                translate=True, tophat=True, noise=True)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
    fig.add_subplot(121)
    plt.imshow(np.transpose(new_x, axes=(1,2,0)))
    fig.add_subplot(122)
    plt.imshow(np.squeeze(new_y))
